1
00:04:20,685 --> 00:04:22,084
<i>Saigon,</i>

2
00:04:23,855 --> 00:04:25,823
<i>Shit,</i>

3
00:04:26,992 --> 00:04:29,790
<i>I'm still only in Saigon,</i>

4
00:04:37,536 --> 00:04:41,700
<i>Every time, I think I'm gonna
wake up back in the jungle,</i>

5
00:04:47,078 --> 00:04:50,639
<i>When I was home after my
first tour, it was worse,</i>

6
00:04:59,024 --> 00:05:01,822
<i>I'd wake up and there'd be nothing,</i>

7
00:05:09,501 --> 00:05:14,268
<i>I hardly said a word to my wife
until I said yes to a divorce,</i>

8
00:05:16,741 --> 00:05:19,710
<i>When I was here, I wanted to be there,</i>

9
00:05:20,312 --> 00:05:25,477
<i>When I was there, all I could think
of was getting back into the jungle,</i>

10
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:30,784
<i>I'm here a week now,</i>

11
00:05:33,925 --> 00:05:36,155
<i>Waiting for a mission,</i>

12
00:05:36,995 --> 00:05:39,020
<i>Getting softer,</i>

13
00:05:43,969 --> 00:05:47,268
<i>Every minute I stay in
this room, I get weaker,</i>

14
00:05:47,472 --> 00:05:51,738
<i>And every minute Charlie squats
in the bush, he gets stronger,</i>

15
00:05:56,448 --> 00:06:01,181
<i>Each time I looked around, the
walls moved in a little tighter,</i>

16
00:07:40,085 --> 00:07:42,952
<i>Everyone gets everything he wants,</i>

17
00:07:43,722 --> 00:07:45,917
<i>I wanted a mission,</i>

18
00:07:46,391 --> 00:07:49,292
<i>and for my sins, they gave me one,</i>

19
00:07:50,395 --> 00:07:52,863
<i>Brought it up to me like room service,</i>

20
00:07:53,631 --> 00:07:56,065
Captain Willard, are you in there?

21
00:07:56,701 --> 00:07:58,669
Yeah, I'm coming.

22
00:07:58,870 --> 00:08:01,668
<i>It was a real choice mission,</i>

23
00:08:01,873 --> 00:08:04,137
<i>And when it was over,</i>

24
00:08:04,442 --> 00:08:06,808
<i>I'd never want another,</i>

25
00:08:14,352 --> 00:08:15,546
What do you want?

26
00:08:15,754 --> 00:08:18,848
- Are you all right, captain?
- What does it look like?

27
00:08:28,166 --> 00:08:30,828
- Are you Willard, 505th Battalion?
- Affirmative.

28
00:08:31,035 --> 00:08:32,434
- 173rd Airborne?
- Yeah.

29
00:08:32,637 --> 00:08:36,095
- Assigned to SOG?
- Hey, buddy, gonna shut the door?

30
00:08:38,176 --> 00:08:40,974
We have orders to escort you to the airfield.

31
00:08:43,848 --> 00:08:46,078
- What are the charges?
- Sir?

32
00:08:46,284 --> 00:08:49,048
- What did I do?
- There's no charges, captain.

33
00:08:49,254 --> 00:08:53,190
You have orders to report to
COMSEC Intelligence at Nha Trang.

34
00:08:54,459 --> 00:08:55,926
Now, you see? All right?

35
00:08:56,127 --> 00:08:59,119
- Nha Trang, for me?
- That's right.

36
00:08:59,931 --> 00:09:02,422
Come on, captain. You still have
a few hours to get cleaned up.

37
00:09:02,634 --> 00:09:06,195
- I'm not feeling too good.
- Captain?

38
00:09:07,472 --> 00:09:09,997
Dave, come here and give me
a hand. We got a dead one.

39
00:09:10,208 --> 00:09:12,540
Come on, captain. Let's take a shower.

40
00:09:12,744 --> 00:09:14,541
- Don't be an asshole.
- Get ahold of him good.

41
00:09:14,746 --> 00:09:17,306
We're gonna take a shower, captain. In we go.

42
00:09:17,515 --> 00:09:19,676
Stand underneath this, captain.

43
00:09:31,563 --> 00:09:33,622
<i>I was going to the worst place in the world</i>

44
00:09:33,832 --> 00:09:36,130
<i>and I didn't even know it yet,</i>

45
00:09:37,101 --> 00:09:39,592
<i>Weeks away and hundreds of miles up a river</i>

46
00:09:39,804 --> 00:09:42,932
<i>that snaked through the war
like a main circuit cable,</i>

47
00:09:43,141 --> 00:09:45,837
<i>plugged straight into Kurtz,</i>

48
00:09:48,613 --> 00:09:51,047
<i>It was no accident that
I got to be the caretaker</i>

49
00:09:51,249 --> 00:09:53,717
<i>of Colonel Walter E, Kurtz's memory</i>

50
00:09:53,918 --> 00:09:57,684
<i>any more than being back
in Saigon was an accident,</i>

51
00:09:58,957 --> 00:10:02,984
<i>There is no way to tell his
story without telling my own,</i>

52
00:10:03,261 --> 00:10:05,161
<i>And if his story is really a confession,</i>

53
00:10:05,363 --> 00:10:06,489
Captain Willard reporting, sir.

54
00:10:06,698 --> 00:10:07,665
<i>Then so is mine,</i>

55
00:10:07,866 --> 00:10:11,029
- Captain. Good. Come on in.
- Thank you, sir.

56
00:10:11,236 --> 00:10:12,931
Stand at ease.

57
00:10:13,304 --> 00:10:14,862
General.

58
00:10:16,441 --> 00:10:18,375
Do you want a cigarette?

59
00:10:19,143 --> 00:10:21,043
No, thank you, sir.

60
00:10:22,213 --> 00:10:25,080
Captain, have you ever
seen this gentleman before?

61
00:10:25,283 --> 00:10:28,309
- No, sir.
- Met the general or myself?

62
00:10:28,519 --> 00:10:30,919
No, sir. Not personally.

63
00:10:31,923 --> 00:10:34,016
You've worked a lot on your
own, haven't you, captain?

64
00:10:34,225 --> 00:10:35,522
Yes, sir, I have.

65
00:10:35,727 --> 00:10:37,752
Your report specifies
intelligence, counterintelligence

66
00:10:37,962 --> 00:10:39,259
with COMSEC I Corps.

67
00:10:39,464 --> 00:10:41,762
I'm not presently disposed to
discuss those operations, sir.

68
00:10:51,476 --> 00:10:54,809
Did you not work for the CIA in I Corps?

69
00:10:56,214 --> 00:10:57,181
No, sir.

70
00:10:57,382 --> 00:10:59,748
Did you not assassinate a
government tax collector,

71
00:10:59,951 --> 00:11:02,784
Quang Tr Province, June 18, 1968?

72
00:11:05,390 --> 00:11:06,948
Captain?

73
00:11:08,393 --> 00:11:14,093
Sir, I am unaware of any
such activity or operation.

74
00:11:14,766 --> 00:11:19,032
Nor would I be disposed to
discuss such an operation

75
00:11:19,237 --> 00:11:22,673
if it did in fact exist, sir.

76
00:11:33,584 --> 00:11:35,779
I thought we'd have a bite
of lunch while we talk.

77
00:11:35,987 --> 00:11:39,320
I hope you brought a good appetite, captain.

78
00:11:39,924 --> 00:11:42,518
I noticed that you have a...

79
00:11:43,561 --> 00:11:45,256
...bad hand there. Are you wounded?

80
00:11:45,463 --> 00:11:47,363
I had a little fishing
accident on R and R, sir.

81
00:11:47,966 --> 00:11:50,867
- Fishing on R and R.
- Yes, sir.

82
00:11:51,069 --> 00:11:53,299
But you're feeling fit?
You're ready for duty?

83
00:11:53,504 --> 00:11:55,802
Yes, general. Very much so, sir.

84
00:11:56,174 --> 00:12:02,079
Well, let's see what we have here.
Roast beef, and usually it's not bad.

85
00:12:03,181 --> 00:12:06,116
Try some, Jerry, and pass it around.

86
00:12:06,317 --> 00:12:10,253
To save a little time,
we might pass both ways.

87
00:12:12,790 --> 00:12:16,920
Captain, I don't know how
you feel about this shrimp,

88
00:12:17,562 --> 00:12:21,760
but if you'll eat it, you'll never have
to prove your courage in any other way.

89
00:12:22,633 --> 00:12:26,228
Actually, why don't I just take a piece here.

90
00:12:26,838 --> 00:12:31,036
Captain, you've heard of
Colonel Walter E. Kurtz?

91
00:12:32,944 --> 00:12:34,309
Yes, sir, I've heard the name.

92
00:12:34,512 --> 00:12:36,343
Oh, Jesus.

93
00:12:36,547 --> 00:12:39,141
Operations officer, 5th Special Forces.

94
00:12:39,350 --> 00:12:42,319
Luke, would you play that
tape for the captain, please?

95
00:12:42,520 --> 00:12:45,489
- Yes, sir. I'm sorry, sir.
- Listen to this carefully, captain.

96
00:12:48,092 --> 00:12:50,890
<i>October 9, 0430 hours,
sector Peter, Victor, King,</i>

97
00:12:51,095 --> 00:12:53,655
These were monitored out of Cambodia.

98
00:12:54,732 --> 00:12:56,962
This has been verified
as Colonel Kurtz's voice.

99
00:12:57,168 --> 00:13:01,070
<i>I watched a snail</i>

100
00:13:01,372 --> 00:13:03,602
<i>crawl along the edge</i>

101
00:13:04,242 --> 00:13:05,766
<i>of a straight razor,</i>

102
00:13:07,812 --> 00:13:09,712
<i>That's my dream,</i>

103
00:13:11,416 --> 00:13:13,646
<i>It's my nightmare,</i>

104
00:13:15,787 --> 00:13:18,415
<i>Crawling, slithering</i>

105
00:13:18,923 --> 00:13:20,914
<i>along the edge...</i>

106
00:13:22,160 --> 00:13:26,392
<i>...of a straight razor...</i>

107
00:13:27,665 --> 00:13:29,895
<i>...and surviving,</i>

108
00:13:32,070 --> 00:13:36,530
<i>Transmission 11, received
'68, December 30, 0500 hours,</i>

109
00:13:36,741 --> 00:13:39,039
<i>Sector King, Zulu, King,</i>

110
00:13:40,411 --> 00:13:42,379
<i>But we must kill them,</i>

111
00:13:42,580 --> 00:13:44,980
<i>We must incinerate them,</i>

112
00:13:45,183 --> 00:13:47,583
<i>Pig after pig,</i>

113
00:13:47,952 --> 00:13:49,681
<i>Cow after cow,</i>

114
00:13:51,689 --> 00:13:56,058
<i>Village after village, Army after army,</i>

115
00:13:56,527 --> 00:13:58,859
<i>And they call me an assassin,</i>

116
00:13:59,063 --> 00:14:04,399
<i>What do you call it when the
assassins accuse the assassin?</i>

117
00:14:04,802 --> 00:14:06,429
<i>They lie,</i>

118
00:14:06,637 --> 00:14:09,197
<i>They lie, and we have to be merciful</i>

119
00:14:09,407 --> 00:14:11,466
<i>for those who lie,</i>

120
00:14:12,009 --> 00:14:15,945
<i>Those nabobs,</i>

121
00:14:17,014 --> 00:14:19,073
<i>I hate them,</i>

122
00:14:19,884 --> 00:14:22,011
<i>I do hate them,</i>

123
00:14:27,191 --> 00:14:30,024
Walt Kurtz was one of the
most outstanding officers

124
00:14:30,228 --> 00:14:32,526
this country's ever produced.

125
00:14:32,730 --> 00:14:35,927
He was brilliant. He was
outstanding in every way.

126
00:14:36,767 --> 00:14:42,034
And he was a good man
too. A humanitarian man.

127
00:14:42,707 --> 00:14:45,267
A man of wit and humor.

128
00:14:45,910 --> 00:14:48,208
He joined the Special Forces.

129
00:14:49,947 --> 00:14:52,279
And after that...

130
00:14:53,718 --> 00:14:57,745
...his ideas, methods...

131
00:14:59,023 --> 00:15:00,615
...became...

132
00:15:02,960 --> 00:15:04,791
...unsound.

133
00:15:09,667 --> 00:15:11,396
Unsound.

134
00:15:16,741 --> 00:15:19,369
Now he's crossed into Cambodia with this

135
00:15:19,577 --> 00:15:25,345
Montagnard army of his that
worship the man like a god

136
00:15:25,550 --> 00:15:29,509
and follow every order, however ridiculous.

137
00:15:30,821 --> 00:15:34,814
Well, I have some other
shocking news to tell you.

138
00:15:35,426 --> 00:15:38,361
Colonel Kurtz was about to be

139
00:15:38,563 --> 00:15:40,497
arrested for murder.

140
00:15:41,332 --> 00:15:44,267
I don't follow, sir. Murdered who?

141
00:15:44,468 --> 00:15:48,529
Kurtz had ordered the execution of
some Vietnamese intelligence agents,

142
00:15:48,739 --> 00:15:52,004
men he believed were double agents.

143
00:15:52,910 --> 00:15:55,572
So he took matters into his own hands.

144
00:15:57,515 --> 00:16:00,040
Well, you see, Willard,

145
00:16:00,551 --> 00:16:03,145
in this war, things get...

146
00:16:03,888 --> 00:16:06,379
...confused out there.

147
00:16:06,857 --> 00:16:10,315
Power, ideals, the old morality

148
00:16:10,528 --> 00:16:13,156
and practical military necessity.

149
00:16:15,333 --> 00:16:18,200
But out there with these natives,

150
00:16:18,869 --> 00:16:22,999
it must be a temptation to...

151
00:16:23,708 --> 00:16:25,403
...be God.

152
00:16:28,512 --> 00:16:32,107
Because there's a conflict
in every human heart

153
00:16:32,817 --> 00:16:35,718
between the rational and the irrational,

154
00:16:36,554 --> 00:16:38,647
between good and evil,

155
00:16:39,924 --> 00:16:42,859
and good does not always triumph.

156
00:16:44,895 --> 00:16:46,863
Sometimes...

157
00:16:47,965 --> 00:16:49,933
...the dark side

158
00:16:50,301 --> 00:16:54,829
overcomes what Lincoln called
"the better angels of our nature. "

159
00:16:56,540 --> 00:16:59,008
Every man has got a breaking point.

160
00:16:59,877 --> 00:17:02,243
You and I have them.

161
00:17:03,447 --> 00:17:06,041
Walt Kurtz has reached his...

162
00:17:07,385 --> 00:17:10,786
...and very obviously, he has gone insane.

163
00:17:23,501 --> 00:17:27,232
Yes, sir. Very much so,
sir. Obviously insane.

164
00:17:31,876 --> 00:17:36,973
Your mission is to proceed up the
Nung River in a Navy patrol boat,

165
00:17:37,448 --> 00:17:40,576
pick up Colonel Kurtz's path at Nu Mung Bha,

166
00:17:40,785 --> 00:17:43,618
follow it, learn what you can along the way.

167
00:17:43,821 --> 00:17:47,723
When you find the colonel,
infiltrate his team

168
00:17:47,925 --> 00:17:49,859
by whatever means available,

169
00:17:50,061 --> 00:17:52,120
and terminate the colonel's command.

170
00:17:58,369 --> 00:18:01,099
Terminate the colonel.

171
00:18:02,006 --> 00:18:06,170
He's out there operating
without any decent restraint,

172
00:18:06,377 --> 00:18:10,438
totally beyond the pale of any acceptable

173
00:18:10,648 --> 00:18:12,309
human conduct,

174
00:18:12,650 --> 00:18:16,051
and he is still in the
field, commanding troops.

175
00:18:16,887 --> 00:18:21,221
Terminate with extreme prejudice.

176
00:18:22,126 --> 00:18:26,654
You understand, captain, that
this mission does not exist,

177
00:18:27,298 --> 00:18:29,789
nor will it ever exist.

178
00:19:24,388 --> 00:19:27,357
<i>How many people had I already killed?</i>

179
00:19:28,225 --> 00:19:31,422
<i>There were those six that
I knew about for sure...</i>

180
00:19:32,096 --> 00:19:35,759
<i>...close enough to blow
their last breath in my face,</i>

181
00:19:37,568 --> 00:19:41,004
<i>But this time, it was an American...</i>

182
00:19:41,405 --> 00:19:43,305
<i>...and an officer,</i>

183
00:19:54,151 --> 00:19:57,052
<i>That wasn't supposed to
make any difference to me,</i>

184
00:19:57,254 --> 00:19:58,881
<i>but it did,</i>

185
00:20:01,025 --> 00:20:02,515
<i>Shit,</i>

186
00:20:02,726 --> 00:20:04,421
<i>Charging a man with murder in this place</i>

187
00:20:04,628 --> 00:20:08,394
<i>was like handing out speeding
tickets at the Indy 500,</i>

188
00:20:10,301 --> 00:20:11,996
<i>I took the mission,</i>

189
00:20:12,203 --> 00:20:14,694
<i>What the hell else was I gonna do?</i>

190
00:20:16,340 --> 00:20:19,707
<i>But I really didn't know
what I'd do when I found him,</i>

191
00:20:26,884 --> 00:20:29,352
Did you check the tank?

192
00:20:29,787 --> 00:20:31,311
Yeah.

193
00:20:32,790 --> 00:20:36,248
<i>I was being ferried down
the coast in a Navy PBR,</i>

194
00:20:36,460 --> 00:20:40,920
<i>a type of plastic patrol boat, a
pretty common sight on the rivers,</i>

195
00:20:41,131 --> 00:20:42,996
<i>They said it was a good
way to pick up information</i>

196
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:47,762
<i>and move without drawing a lot
of attention, and that was okay,</i>

197
00:20:47,972 --> 00:20:50,736
<i>I needed the air and the time,</i>

198
00:20:51,509 --> 00:20:53,374
<i>Only problem was I wouldn't be alone,</i>

199
00:20:53,577 --> 00:20:55,477
Morning, captain.

200
00:20:57,748 --> 00:21:00,876
<i>The crew were mostly just kids,</i>

201
00:21:01,085 --> 00:21:04,543
<i>rock 'n' rollers with
one foot in their graves,</i>

202
00:21:05,155 --> 00:21:08,556
- How old are you?
- Seventeen.

203
00:21:09,059 --> 00:21:12,256
<i>The machinist, the one they
called Chef, was from New Orleans,</i>

204
00:21:12,463 --> 00:21:15,159
<i>He was wrapped too tight for Vietnam,</i>

205
00:21:15,366 --> 00:21:17,027
<i>Probably wrapped too tight for New Orleans,</i>

206
00:21:19,326 --> 00:21:21,021
<i>Lance, on the forward
50s, was a famous surfer</i>

207
00:21:21,228 --> 00:21:22,855
<i>from the beaches south of L, A,</i>

208
00:21:28,836 --> 00:21:33,034
<i>Clean, Mr, Clean, was from
some South Bronx shithole,</i>

209
00:21:33,240 --> 00:21:35,174
<i>and I think the light
and the space of Vietnam</i>

210
00:21:35,375 --> 00:21:37,969
<i>really put the zap on his head,</i>

211
00:21:40,581 --> 00:21:42,845
<i>Then there was Phillips, the chief,</i>

212
00:21:43,050 --> 00:21:46,679
<i>It might have been my mission, but
it sure as shit was the chief's boat,</i>

213
00:21:46,887 --> 00:21:49,117
There's about two points
where we can draw enough water

214
00:21:49,323 --> 00:21:51,348
to get into the Nung River.

215
00:21:51,558 --> 00:21:54,755
They're both hot. Belong to Charlie.

216
00:21:55,863 --> 00:21:57,728
Don't worry about it.

217
00:21:58,398 --> 00:22:00,025
Don't smoke.

218
00:22:01,602 --> 00:22:04,628
You know, I've pulled a
few special ops in here.

219
00:22:04,938 --> 00:22:07,133
About six months ago,

220
00:22:07,608 --> 00:22:11,305
I took a man who was going
up past the bridge at Do Lung.

221
00:22:12,012 --> 00:22:14,572
He was regular Army too.

222
00:22:16,683 --> 00:22:19,151
Heard he shot himself in the head.

223
00:22:34,167 --> 00:22:35,134
<i>Good morning, Vietnam,</i>

224
00:22:35,335 --> 00:22:37,803
<i>I'm Army Specialist Zack Johnson on AMVN,</i>

225
00:22:38,005 --> 00:22:41,532
<i>It's about 82 degrees in downtown
Saigon right now, also very humid,</i>

226
00:22:41,742 --> 00:22:43,733
<i>And we have an important message for all Gls</i>

227
00:22:43,944 --> 00:22:46,071
<i>who are living off-base
from the mayor of Saigon,</i>

228
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:47,247
Yeah!

229
00:22:47,447 --> 00:22:50,678
<i>He'd like you to hang your laundry
indoors instead of on the windowsills,</i>

230
00:22:50,884 --> 00:22:53,978
<i>The mayor wants you to keep Saigon beautiful,</i>

231
00:22:54,187 --> 00:22:55,620
<i>Here's another blast from the past</i>

232
00:22:55,822 --> 00:22:58,518
<i>going out to Big Sam, who's
alone in the mantle room out there</i>

233
00:22:58,725 --> 00:23:01,990
<i>with the 1 st Battalion, 35th
Infantry, and dedicated by the fire team</i>

234
00:23:02,195 --> 00:23:04,720
<i>at An Khe to their groovy CO Fred the Head;</i>

235
00:23:04,932 --> 00:23:07,867
